Mel Avina-Beltran

This week, we will be tracking changes in income by race/ethnicity and gender from 1940 to 2000. In this notebook, you will learn how to deal with several issues that are unique to income analysis: sample-line weights, top-coding, and adjusting for inflation. You will also learn to make boxplots.

Getting started

Load the tidyverse library and read the wk10.csv file into a data frame called ipums. Use the names function to see what variables are in this data set.

library(tidyverse)
ipums <-read.csv("wk10.csv") 
names(ipums)

Create a factor variable for sex called SEXF.

ipums <- ipums %>% mutate(SEXF = factor(SEX,labels=c("Male","Female")))

Classifying race and ethnicity

When we graph income over time, we want to take race and ethnicity into account. We will do that with the HISPAN and RACESING variables. We are using RACESING instead of RACE or RACED because IPUMS constructed RACESING to be consistent before and after the year 2000 (when people could start identifying with more than one race category). We need to use HISPAN to identify whether or not a person was Hispanic.

New variables

We will start by exploring these variables. Convert each one into a factor, then make a two-way table of HISPANF and RACESINGF.

ipums <- ipums %>% mutate(HISPANF = factor(HISPAN,labels=c("Not Hispanic","Mexican","Puerto Rican","Cuban","Other")),
                            RACESINGF = factor(RACESING,labels=c("White","Black","Native","Asian/Pacific","Other")))

Now we will use the HISPAN and RACESING variables to create a new variable in the ipums data frame called RACETH that classifies people into five mutually-exclusive categories: Hispanic, NH White, NH Black, NH Native, and NH Asian/Pacific. Do not include people classified as “Other”. Use two-way tables to make sure your new variables look the way you expect.

ipums <- ipums %>% filter(RACESINGF != "Other") %>% mutate(RACETH = ifelse(HISPAN > 0,0,RACESING)) %>%
                mutate(RACETH = factor(RACETH, labels=c("Hispanic","NH White","NH Black","NH Native","NH Asian/Pacific")))

Income

Universe for income variables

Questions about income were not asked of everyone. For this reason, we need to limit our analysis to individuals aged 16 and over who are not living in institutions (GQ != 3). Apply the appropriate filters, saving as a new dataframe called income, and test to make sure you have done it correctly.

income <- ipums %>% filter(AGE >=16 & GQ != 3)

You can see that in some years we have unrealistically high incomes (especially given what we know about top-coding). This is because IPUMS uses 999998 and 999999 as missing value codes. Keep this in mind when we use this variable.

We need to use the CPI99 variable to adjust for inflation. CPI99 is a multiplier that you will use to convert contemporary dollars in each year to 1999 dollars. Since the 2000 census collected information about income earned in 1999, the multiplier for that year is 1. The multiplier gets bigger as we go farther back in time because money decreases in value as time goes on (inflation).

Create a new variable in the income data frame called ADJINC (adjusted income) that represents each person’s income in 1999 dollars. Do this only for individuals who have a valid response for INCWAGE. Then list the maximum income for each year.

income <- income %>% mutate(ADJINC = ifelse(INCWAGE < 999998,INCWAGE*CPI99,0))
for (year in unique(income$YEAR)) {
  print(year)
  print(max(filter(income, YEAR == year)$ADJINC))
}

This shows the inflation-adjusted top code for each year.

Working with sample-line variables and weights

Only a small sample of people was asked their income in 1950. These were known as “sample-line” people. For that reason, when we work with the INCWAGE variable, we need to weight the 1950 data by SLWT (sample-line weight) instead of PERWT (person weight).

To accomplish that, we will create a new variable called WEIGHT. In 1950, WEIGHT will be equal to SLWT; in all other years, it will be equal to PERWT.

income <- income %>% mutate(WEIGHT = ifelse(YEAR==1950,SLWT,PERWT))

To see the results, use summary() to produce univariate statistics for WEIGHT in each year

for (year in sort(unique(income$YEAR))) {
  print(year)
  print(summary(filter(income, YEAR == year)$WEIGHT))
}

Calculating the median

Let’s start by making a line graph showing the percentage of people who reported some income in each census. Use line color to represent race/ethnicity and facet by sex. We will include points on the line to indicate when observations were made.

income %>% mutate(INC = ADJINC>0) %>% group_by(YEAR,RACETH,SEXF) %>% count(INC,wt=WEIGHT) %>% mutate(TOTAL=sum(n)) %>% filter(INC) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=YEAR,y=n/TOTAL,color=RACETH)) + geom_line(size=2) + geom_point(size=5) + facet_grid(cols=vars(SEXF)) + theme_minimal(base_size = 50) + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1940,2000,20)) + scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) + scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set2") + labs(x="Census Year", y="Percent of Noninstitutional Population Aged 16+", color="Race/Ethnicity",title="Percent of Noninstitutional Population Aged 16+ who reported earned income")

In your lab, you will make a line graph showing median income over time for people who reported income, with line color representing race and facets for sex. The first thing you will need to do is group by YEAR, RACETH, and SEXF and use the summarize() function to calculate the median income for each group. You will need use the rep() function inside the summarize() function to weight by WEIGHT. To get a sense of how this works, let’s look at a fake data set about pets.

head(pet_owners)

If we want to see how many pet owners go to each university, we can use the count() function we have already been working with.

pet_owners %>% group_by(school) %>% count()

If we want to see the number of dogs owned by students from each university, we can use the summarize() function.

pet_owners %>% group_by(school) %>% summarize(total_dogs = sum(dogs))

We can also get the number of cats.

pet_owners %>% group_by(school) %>% summarize(total_dogs = sum(dogs), total_cats = sum(cats))

Now imagine that each in the list has a twin with the exact same number of dogs and cats (each twin has their own cats and dogs, but they have the same number). In that case, each person in this data frame actually represents two people, so we want to weight each observation by two. We can do that with the rep() function, which simply repeats a value as many times as we want.

pet_owners$dogs
 [1] 4 1 0 2 3 0 2 1 2 1 1 2 1 3 4 1 3 2 1 0 1 0 2 1 1 2
rep(pet_owners$dogs, 2)
 [1] 4 1 0 2 3 0 2 1 2 1 1 2 1 3 4 1 3 2 1 0 1 0 2 1 1 2 4 1 0 2 3 0 2 1 2 1 1 2 1 3 4 1 3 2 1 0 1 0 2 1 1 2

If we want to get the total number of dogs and cats, we can do this.

pet_owners %>% group_by(school) %>% summarize(total_dogs = sum(rep(dogs, 2)), total_cats = sum(rep(cats, 2)))

But what if some people don’t have twins, and some people are triplets or quadruplets? This data frame shows how many siblings each person in the original data frame represents (if someone is a twin, they represent two siblings).

sibsets <- tribble(
  ~name, ~siblings,
  "Alex", 1,
  "Becky", 2,
  "Carlos", 1,
  "Dina", 3,
  "Evgeny", 1,
  "Frida", 1,
  "Greg", 4,
  "Harriet",2,
  "Ivan", 1,
  "Jane", 1,
  "Kirk", 1,
  "Libby", 2,
  "Mort", 3,
  "Nadia", 2,

  "Raina", 2, 
  "Steve", 1,

  "Ulysses", 1, 
  "Viola", 2,
  "Warren", 2, 
  "Xena", 1, 
  "Yves", 1, 
  "Zadie", 2
)
head(sibsets)

We can join this to the pet_owners data frame. Then we can use the siblings column as the second argument to the rep() function instead of the number 2 to calculate the total number of dogs and cats across sibsets at each university.

inner_join(pet_owners, sibsets) %>% group_by(school) %>%
  summarize(total_dogs = sum(rep(dogs, siblings)), total_cats = sum(rep(cats, siblings)))
Joining, by = "name"

Apparently UCD students have more siblings than CSUS students. With the summarize() function, we can use any summary function. Above we used sum(), but if we want to test our proposition that UCD students have more siblings than CSUS students, we can calculate the median sibset size for each person in the original data frame.

inner_join(pet_owners, sibsets) %>% group_by(school) %>%
  summarize(sibset_size = median(siblings))
Joining, by = "name"

We can also calculate the median number of dogs and cats at each university. Remember that each sibling has their own pets.

inner_join(pet_owners, sibsets) %>% group_by(school) %>%
  summarize(median_dogs = median(rep(dogs, siblings)), median_cats = median(rep(cats, siblings)))
Joining, by = "name"

Now we will use the same concept to calculate the median income in each year for people reporting income. In your lab, you will need to do the same thing, but by sex and race/ethnicity, and then you will need to graph it.

income %>% filter(ADJINC > 0 ) %>% group_by(YEAR) %>% summarize(MEDINC=median(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT)))
NA

Boxplots

Our new visualization for this week is the boxplot. You can see an example of a boxplot here. Ours will be a bit different because we will use the 10th percentile and 90th percentile instead of the minimum and maximum.

Before we graph the boxplots, we will need to use the summary() function to calculate the 10th percentile (MIN), 25th percentile (LOW), median (MED), 75th percentile (HIGH), and 90th percentile (MAX) for income (including only people who reported income). We will do this by year and sex now; in your lab you will also need to facet by race/ethnicity. We will save these summaries in a data frame called inc_sum.

inc_sum <- income %>% filter(ADJINC > 0) %>%
              group_by(YEAR, SEXF) %>%
              summarize(MIN = quantile(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT), 0.1),
                        LOW = quantile(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT), 0.25),
                        MED = quantile(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT), 0.5),
                        HIGH = quantile(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT), 0.75),
                        MAX = quantile(rep(ADJINC,WEIGHT), 0.9))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'YEAR'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
head(inc_sum)

Now we can plot the boxplot using ggplot().

ggplot(inc_sum, aes(x=factor(YEAR),fill=SEXF)) +
         geom_boxplot(aes(ymin=MIN,lower=LOW,middle=MED,upper=HIGH,ymax=MAX),stat="identity",position="dodge") + theme_minimal(base_size=35) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") + scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar) + labs(x="Census Year", y="1999 Dollars", fill="Sex", title="income distribution for noninstitutional population reporting income and aged 16+ (whiskers indicate 10th and 90th percentiles)")
